Diana Taurasi scored 22 points despite playing most of the second half with four fouls, helping top-ranked
Connecticut survive a scare and beat Boston College (No. 20 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) 83-75 Saturday for its 61st consecutive win.
article.headline: UConn holds off BC down stretch
article.linkText: 61 and counting: UConn survives BC scare
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- Top-ranked Connecticut survived a scare and kept
its winning streak alive.

The Huskies beat Boston College 83-75 on Saturday and won
their 61st game in a row -- the second-longest streak in NCAA
basketball history.

Diana Taurasi scored 22 despite playing most of the second half
with four fouls, converting a three-point play to break a tie with
5:10 left after BC (No. 20 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) scored nine straight points to make it 61-61.

"There's a point in the game where you have to bear down and
make shots,'' said Taurasi, the lone returning starter from last
year's national champions. "The last couple of games, we've been
letting teams back into it. It's something we can fix.''

Barbara Turner had 18 points and nine rebounds for UConn (22-0,
9-0 Big East) before fouling out in the final minute.

Becky Gottstein had 19 points, Clare Droesch scored 17 and they
had eight rebounds apiece for BC (15-6, 7-3). Jessalyn Deveny had
12 points, 10 assists and five rebounds for the Eagles.

"I was nervous going into this game. I was scared to death,''
UConn coach Geno Auriemma said. "Once they tied it up -- we know
what kind of team we are. We're not perfect.''

But they have been -- in the standings, at least -- since a loss
to Notre Dame in the 2001 NCAA Final Four. That includes last
year's 39-0 title team.

With a sold-out crowd of 8,606 evenly split between the home
team and the neighboring dynasty, UConn extended the winning streak
that was already an NCAA women's basketball record. The UCLA men's
team won 88 in a row in the Bill Walton era from 1971-74; Bill
Russell's San Francisco team won 60 in a row from 1955-57.

Connecticut has already had some big games this season, breaking
the women's record with their 55th consecutive victory and then
beating second-ranked Duke 77-65 last week in Durham, N.C.

But for Boston College -- like most of the Huskies' opponents --
the game against UConn is the biggest of the year. Still, they had
no intention of settling for a moral victory.

"Honestly, I'm kind of disappointed because we dug such a big
hole for ourselves at the beginning,'' BC guard Brianne Stepherson
said. "If we had just started out the way we ended it, we would
have had a better game.''

UConn scored 16 consecutive points to take a 20-4 lead and led
27-11 with 9:02 left in the first half. It was 39-27 at the break
and 54-46 midway through the second half when Taurasi picked up
consecutive charging fouls, forcing her to the bench.

UConn led 61-52 with 8:15 left before BC went on a 9-0 run to
tie it for the first time since 4-4. Deveny hit a basket, Droesch
hit a 3-pointer, and after Turner missed the front end of a
one-and-one, Droesch hit a baby hook from 4 feet and Gottstein
scored from the lane to make it 61-all with 5:10 left.

But Taurasi converted a three-point play -- her first points
since she picked up her fourth foul with 10:57 left -- and Ashley
Battle scored on a steal and breakaway to restore UConn's cushion.

It was 72-69 with 2:40 left when Gottstein picked up her fifth
foul. Turner made two free throws, and Taurasi hit a turnaround in
the lane, and BC never got within five points again.
